Marriage of Cousins in Victorian England -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJuxtaposing contributions from geneticists and anthropologists, this volume provides a contemporary overview of cousin marriage and what is happening at the interface of public policy, the management of genetic risk and changing cultural practices in the Middle East and in multi-ethnic Europe. It offers a cross-cultural exploration of practices of cousin marriage in the light of new genetic understanding of consanguineous marriage and its possible health risks. Overall, the volume presents a reflective, interdisciplinary analysis of the social and ethical issues raised by both the discourse of risk in cousin marriage, as well as existing and potential interventions to promote “healthy consanguinity” via new genetic technologies.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCross-cousin marriage. 0aGenetic disorders. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  aanthropologist.  aanthropology.  achild marriage.  aconsanguineous marriage.  aconsanguinity.  acontemporary overview.  acultural anthropology.  adating and marriage.  ademocracy.  adiscourse.  afamily relations.  afamily studies.  agenetic risk.  agenetic technologies.  agenetic understanding.  ageneticist.  agenetics.  ahuman condition.  ainbreeding.  aincest.  ainterdisciplinary analysis.  ainterdisciplinary studies.  alove and marriage.  amiddle east.  amiddle eastern customs.  amulti-ethnic.  amulti-ethnicities.  apolitics.  apublic policies.1 aBartels, Edien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaudevin, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb